{
  "texts": [
    "Our argument, then, isn't that algorithmic recommendation prevents people from being perfect moral agents, free to develop and exercise attentional moral skill in its purest and best form.",
    "Rather, our view is that, in a world that already poses serious challenges for judicious attention allocation, algorithmic recommendation adds yet another challenge, and an especially powerful one at that.",
    "But it doesn't have to.",
    "The problems we've identified aren't intractable.",
    "We'll close, then, by considering how algorithmic recommendation might be reimagined such that it supports, rather than undermines, attentional moral skill."
  ]
}